    icon: "🌅",
    description: "The actions you take in your 20s have more impact on retirement than anything you do later — here's exactly what to do.",
    steps: [
      {
        title: "Understand Why Your 20s Are the Most Valuable Decade",
        content: "Compound interest is often called the eighth wonder of the world — and nowhere is it more powerful than when you start in your 20s.\n\n**The math:**\nInvest $5,000/year from age 22 to 32 (10 years, $50,000 total), then stop completely:\n• At 65: ~$602,000 (at 7% average return)\n\nInvest $5,000/year from age 32 to 65 (33 years, $165,000 total):\n• At 65: ~$640,000\n\nStarting 10 years earlier with one-third the total contribution achieves nearly the same result. Time is the most powerful force in investing.\n\n**What starting late costs:**\nEvery year you delay starting reduces the amount you'll have at retirement significantly — sometimes by hundreds of thousands of dollars.\n\n**What your 20s should establish:**\n• The habit of saving before spending\n• Your first tax-advantaged retirement accounts\n• A diversified, low-cost investment approach\n• An understanding of how the system works\n\nYou don't need to have it all figured out. You need to start.",
        tip: "You don't need to invest thousands to start. Even $50/month invested consistently starting at 22 grows to more than $100,000 by 65 at a 7% return.",
        action: "Calculate how many years you have until age 65. Multiply $7,000 by that number to see what you'd contribute if you maxed a Roth IRA every year — then look up what it grows to using a compound interest calculator."
      },
      {
        title: "Establish Your Emergency Fund First",
        content: "Before maximizing retirement contributions, build a small emergency fund. Without one, a single unexpected expense forces you to stop investing or — worse — withdraw from retirement accounts with penalties.\n\n**Emergency fund targets:**\n• **Starter goal:** $1,000 (minimum; covers most common small emergencies)\n• **Solid foundation:** 3 months of essential expenses\n• **Full target:** 6 months of essential expenses\n\n**Where to keep it:**\nHigh-yield savings account (HYSA) earning 4–5% APY. Not in a checking account (too tempting). Not in the stock market (too volatile — you may need it when markets are down).\n\n**Why this comes before retirement investing:**\nWithout an emergency fund:\n• You take on credit card debt for emergencies (24% APR)\n• You withdraw from retirement accounts early (10% penalty + income taxes)\n• Financial stress undermines every other good habit\n\n**The sequence:**\n1. $1,000 starter emergency fund\n2. Contribute to 401(k) up to employer match\n3. Build emergency fund to 3–6 months\n4. Max Roth IRA\n5. Max 401(k)\n6. Taxable brokerage",
        tip: "Park your emergency fund in a different bank than your checking account. The one extra step of transferring creates just enough friction to prevent impulse withdrawals.",
        action: "Calculate your monthly essential expenses (rent, food, utilities, transportation, minimum debt payments). Multiply by 3 to find your emergency fund target."
      },
      {
        title: "Open and Max Your First Roth IRA",
        content: "For most people in their 20s, the Roth IRA is the single best retirement account available.\n\n**Why Roth is ideal in your 20s:**\n• You're likely in a lower tax bracket than you'll be later\n• Paying taxes now (on a lower income) means tax-free growth and withdrawals forever\n• Flexibility: contributions (not earnings) can be withdrawn anytime without penalty — it works as a backup emergency fund\n• No required minimum distributions — your money can stay invested as long as you want\n\n**2026 Roth IRA contribution limit:** $7,000/year ($583/month)\n\n**You can contribute to a Roth IRA even if you have a 401(k).**\n\n**Where to open one:**\nFidelity, Schwab, or Vanguard. All have no minimums and excellent low-cost index funds.\n\n**What to invest in:**\nFor simplicity and strong long-term returns:\n• A target-date fund matching your expected retirement year (e.g., Target Date 2065)\n• Or a total U.S. market index fund (FZROX at Fidelity, VTSAX at Vanguard)\n\n**If you can't max it yet:**\nContribute what you can. Even $100/month is a meaningful start. Increase contributions with each raise.",
        tip: "Set up automatic monthly contributions to your Roth IRA on payday. You'll adapt to the lower take-home quickly and the habit compounding over decades is transformative.",
        action: "Open a Roth IRA at Fidelity.com, Schwab.com, or Vanguard.com this week if you don't already have one. Set up a monthly automatic contribution of any amount."
      },
      {
        title: "Capture Your Full 401(k) Match",
        content: "If your employer offers a 401(k) match, capturing the full match is the highest guaranteed return in personal finance — and should come before everything except your starter emergency fund.\n\n**A match is free money:**\nA 50% match on up to 6% of your salary is a 50% instant return before any investment growth. There is no safer, higher return available.\n\n**Common match structures:**\n• '100% match up to 3%' → Contribute at least 3%\n• '50% match up to 6%' → Contribute at least 6%\n\n**Beyond the match:**\nAfter capturing the full match, prioritize your Roth IRA ($7,000/year) before putting additional money into the 401(k). Roth IRA gives you more investment choices and flexibility.\n\n**Then:** Come back and increase 401(k) contributions toward the $23,500 annual limit.\n\n**Investment selection in your 401(k):**\nChoose the lowest-cost index funds available. Look for funds with 'index' in the name and expense ratios under 0.20%. Avoid actively managed funds with high fees.\n\n**Target-date funds in your 401(k):**\nIf you're unsure, a target-date fund is a perfectly reasonable one-fund solution — it automatically diversifies and rebalances.",
        tip: "Increase your 401(k) contribution by 1% every time you get a raise. You won't miss money you never had in your paycheck, and the habit accelerates wealth-building significantly over a career.",
        action: "Log into your employer's benefits portal and verify your 401(k) contribution is at least enough to capture the full employer match."
      },
      {
        title: "Build Good Habits That Compound Over Time",
        content: "Retirement planning in your 20s isn't just about the accounts you open — it's about the financial habits you build that sustain decades of wealth-building.\n\n**The most important habits:**\n\n**Live below your means:**\nAs your income grows, resist the urge to inflate your lifestyle proportionally. Keeping lifestyle costs stable while income grows (sometimes called 'stealth wealth') is one of the most reliable paths to financial independence.\n\n**Avoid lifestyle inflation:**\nWhen you get a raise, split it: 50% to lifestyle improvement, 50% to savings/investments. Don't let every income increase be fully absorbed by spending.\n\n**Increase savings rate annually:**\nAim for a savings rate of 15–20% of gross income for retirement by your late 20s. This includes employer contributions.\n\n**Don't touch retirement accounts:**\nEarly withdrawal penalties (10% + income tax) are devastating. Treat your retirement accounts as locked until 59½ (except Roth IRA contributions, which can be withdrawn anytime).\n\n**Learn continuously:**\nFinancial literacy compounds too. Understanding tax strategies, investment options, and planning tools gives you an edge that grows over a career.\n\n**Check in annually:**\nOnce a year, review your accounts, rebalance if needed, and confirm you're on track for your retirement goals.",
        tip: "A savings rate of even 20% of income in your 20s makes financial independence by your mid-50s realistic. The math is on your side if you start early enough.",
        action: "Calculate your current savings rate: (monthly savings + retirement contributions) ÷ gross monthly income × 100. Set a target to increase it by 2% over the next 12 months."
      }
    ]
